<h3>Miner's Helmet</h3>
<p>The Miner's Helmet is a mobile light source that consumes 1 durability every <strong>30 seconds</strong> under normal rules and every <strong>15 seconds</strong> in Hardcore. It is crafted at an <strong>Iron Workbench</strong> after unlocking the related Knowledge Book, and it must be worn in the <strong>accessory slot</strong>. A Battery restores <strong>75</strong> durability normally or <strong>50</strong> in Hardcore.</p>
<div class="tip-card">⛏️ <strong>Repairing:</strong> apply Batteries on an <strong>iron or better anvil</strong>. At <strong>0 durability</strong> the helmet does not disappear; it simply stops providing light until repaired.</div>
<div class="tip-card">💡 Spare Knowledge Books can be converted into regular Books at the workbench for XP.</div>
<div class="tip-card">🪙 <strong><span class="wiki-item" data-id="hardstone_coin">Hardstone Coin</span>:</strong> crafted from 1 Hardstone Nugget, it costs <strong>300 XP</strong> to make, but that XP is returned when you convert it back into nuggets. In practice this makes it a simple <strong>XP storage item</strong> when you want to park experience in an object temporarily.</div>
<div class="tip-card">🗿 <strong><span class="wiki-item" data-id="way_stone">Waystone</span>:</strong> the local item-doc treats it as an activated long-distance travel anchor. Its explicitly documented world source is the <strong>top floor of the Underground World's Mushroom Forest Battle Tower</strong>. The local item-info still notes <strong>free travel within 500 blocks</strong>, then <strong>100 XP for each additional 300 blocks</strong>. Older <strong>Return / Bound / Warp Scroll</strong> references still appear in the files, but the current recipe set leaves them in a <strong>legacy / removed</strong> state.</div>
<div class="tip-card">🌀 <strong><span class="wiki-item" data-id="conveying_stone">Teleportation Stone</span>:</strong> this is <strong>not the same</strong> as the Waystone. The local item-info describes it as part of a <strong>4×6 overworld portal-frame</strong> travel system lit with <strong>Flint and Steel</strong>. Different stones bias travel toward <strong>broad biome destinations</strong> such as desert, swamp, plains, plateau, ocean, snowy terrain, or jungle, but they do <strong>not guarantee</strong> a specific ruin.</div>
<div class="tip-card">🔥 <strong><span class="wiki-item" data-id="flint_and_steel">Flint and Steel</span> material ladder:</strong> the local <code>802093_flint_and_steel</code> doc confirms that MiTE:BE has more than the usual iron version. The current line is <strong>Copper 8</strong>, <strong>Silver 10</strong>, <strong>Iron 16</strong>, <strong>Gold 24</strong>, <strong>Hardstone 32</strong>, <strong>Ancient Metal 48</strong>, <strong>Mithril 80</strong>, <strong>Adamantium 144</strong> durability. They all work the same way; higher tiers just need stronger workbenches and last much longer for portals, torches, and relighting jobs.</div>
<div class="tip-card">🏮 <strong><span class="wiki-item" data-id="lantern">Lantern</span> &amp; <span class="wiki-item" data-id="template_lantern">Decorative Lantern</span>:</strong> both are <strong>light level 15</strong> decorative blocks. The normal lantern uses <strong>String + Torch + Red Wool</strong>, while the decorative lantern uses <strong>4 Iron Nuggets + Torch</strong>. The <strong><span class="wiki-item" data-id="glow_stone_torch">Glowstone Torch</span></strong> is another light-15 option, crafted from <strong>Glowstone Dust + Stick</strong>.</div>
<div class="tip-card">🧭 <strong><span class="wiki-item" data-id="empty_map">Empty Map</span> &amp; <span class="wiki-item" data-id="map">Map</span>:</strong> local recipes show the blank map is made from <strong>Book + Compass</strong>, then <strong>right-clicked</strong> to become a normal map. An existing map can be cloned on the workbench with <strong>1 Empty Map</strong>.</div>
<div class="tip-card">🗺️ <strong><span class="wiki-item" data-id="empty_antique_atlas">Empty Antique Atlas</span> &amp; <span class="wiki-item" data-id="antique_atlas">Antique Atlas</span>:</strong> right-clicking the empty version turns it into the full atlas. The finished atlas has its own interface, <strong>biome coloring</strong>, landmark markers, and backup support. The local item-doc says the empty atlas can appear with about a <strong>10%</strong> chance in underground <strong>ancient skeleton spawner</strong> loot.</div>
<div class="tip-card">🚩 <strong><span class="wiki-item" data-id="pillager_flag">Pillager Flag</span>:</strong> can drop from pillagers, and while <strong>held in hand</strong> it <strong>doubles villager trade output</strong> within a <strong>20-block radius</strong>.</div>
</div>

